        "question": "What is the difference between an MVP and a full product for launch speed?",
        "answer": "An MVP (Minimum Viable Product) is the minimum set of features required to validate the core hypothesis with real users not the minimum viable demo, and not a stripped-down version of the full vision, but the minimum that provides enough value for real users to use it and provide meaningful feedback. An MVP is the fastest path to market validation because it eliminates features that are not required for validation. The distinction from a prototype (a demo that shows what the product could do, not a working system that real users can use to accomplish real tasks) and from a full product (the complete feature set the product vision requires). ClickMasters' MVP scoping process: map every proposed feature to the hypothesis it validates, separate MVP features (required for validation) from Phase 2 features (required after validation), and scope the engagement to MVP features only. This typically reduces the scope by 40-60% compared to the founder's initial feature list and reduces the timeline by 4-8 weeks."
